@flexiarg writing-coherence/triad-inflation
@title Make the Third Item Earn Its Place
@keywords triad, rule-of-three, parallelism, list, padding
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/balanced-pair-padding writing-coherence/scope-mush]

! conclusion: Three parallel items where two would do — because three sounds structural — leaves the third item carrying no weight the first two do not.  The triad inflates the appearance of a considered enumeration.  The third term earns its place only when it carries a distinct claim the reader could lose by dropping it.
  + context: The rule of three has genuine force: it signals completeness, rhythm, balance.  It also has genuine cost: a triad invites the writer to round out a pair with a filler term that is a hyponym, synonym, or restatement.  AI prose does this often — "conceptually, structurally, and operationally" — where the three adverbs overlap substantially in meaning.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: parallelism as polish ↔ argumentative weight.
    Real: symmetric lists feel complete and read well.  Asymmetric lists feel unfinished even when they are accurate.
    Irreducible: a list cannot simultaneously optimise rhythm and carry distinct weight per item; one must give.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever a pair would read as incomplete.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Drop the third: if the third item does not carry distinct weight, cut it.  Pairs are not weaker than triads; they are more honest.
    (2) Replace the third with a specific instance: convert the third abstract term into a concrete example that exemplifies both of the first two.  The triad now carries different work per slot.
    (3) Keep all three and declare what each does: if the triad is load-bearing, make the per-slot distinction visible in the surrounding sentences, so the reader can see why three and not two.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: removing the third item changes what the reader would conclude.  Failing when: the third item is a hyponym of, synonym for, or restatement of the first or second.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Adverb stack: "conceptually, structurally, and operationally" where the three overlap.
    - Synonym triad: "robust, durable, and resilient" — three words for one property.
    - Instance promoted to parallel: "physics, chemistry, and the hard sciences generally" — category error disguised as triad.
    - Rhetorical rhythm: the triad appears because two-item lists felt incomplete, not because the third term earned its place.
